# Hub vs Switch

## What is a Hub?

A hub is a basic networking device that connects multiple devices and sends incoming data to every connected port.

### Characteristics

* Operates at Layer 1 (Physical Layer)
* Broadcasts data to all devices
* Does not know where data should go
* Rarely used in modern networks

### Advantages

* Simple
* Low cost

### Disadvantages

* Inefficient
* More network collisions
* Lower security

---

## What is a Switch?

A switch is a networking device that intelligently forwards data only to the intended destination.

### Characteristics

* Operates at Layer 2 (Data Link Layer)
* Uses MAC addresses
* Sends traffic only where it needs to go
* Commonly used in modern networks

### Advantages

* Faster performance
* Better security
* Fewer collisions

### Disadvantages

* More expensive than a hub

---

## Hub vs Switch Comparison

| Feature       | Hub       | Switch             |
| ------------- | --------- | ------------------ |
| OSI Layer     | Layer 1   | Layer 2            |
| Data Delivery | All Ports | Specific Port      |
| Performance   | Lower     | Higher             |
| Security      | Lower     | Higher             |
| Intelligence  | None      | Uses MAC Addresses |

---

## Real-World Example

In a home or office network, devices are usually connected to a switch, not a hub.

---

## Cybersecurity Connection

Understanding switches is important because security analysts investigate traffic moving between devices. Switches use MAC addresses and help reduce unnecessary network traffic.

Knowing the difference between hubs and switches also helps explain collision domains and packet forwarding.

## Key Takeaways

* Hubs send data to everyone.
* Switches send data only to the correct device.
* Modern networks use switches.
* Switches improve performance and security.
What is a Hub?-A hub operates at a layer 1 of the osi model.
What is a Switch?-a switch operates at a layer 2 of the osi model.

## Key Points

- A hub sends data to every connected device.
- A switch sends data only to the intended destination.
- Switches use MAC addresses to forward traffic.
- Switches are faster and more secure than hubs.
- Modern networks primarily use switches.
# Practice Questions & Answers

## 1. What is a hub?

A hub is a Layer 1 networking device that sends incoming data to every connected device on the network.

---

## 2. What is a switch?

A switch is a Layer 2 networking device that forwards data only to the intended destination using MAC addresses.

---

## 3. What OSI layer does a hub operate on?

Layer 1 (Physical Layer).

---

## 4. What OSI layer does a switch operate on?

Layer 2 (Data Link Layer).

---

## 5. What information does a switch use to forward traffic?

A switch uses MAC addresses to determine where data should be sent.

---

## 6. Does a hub send data to one device or all devices?

A hub sends data to all connected devices.

---

## 7. Does a switch send data to one device or all devices?

A switch sends data only to the intended device.

---

## 8. Which device is more efficient, a hub or a switch?

A switch is more efficient because it reduces unnecessary network traffic.

---

## 9. Which device provides better security?

A switch provides better security because network traffic is sent only to the intended destination.

---

## 10. Why are hubs rarely used today?

Hubs are inefficient, create more network traffic, and provide less security than switches.

---

## 11. Which device is commonly found in modern networks?

Switches are commonly used in modern home, office, and enterprise networks.

---

## 12. What is one advantage of a hub?

Hubs are simple and inexpensive.

---

## 13. What is one advantage of a switch ?

Switches improve network performance by forwarding traffic only where it needs to go.

---

## 14. What is one disadvantage of a hub?

A hub broadcasts all traffic to every device, creating unnecessary traffic.

---

## 15. In a modern office network, would you choose a hub or a switch?

A switch, because it provides better performance, scalability, and security.

